		<item>
		<title>Travel diary: work, friends, and a trip to Santiago</title>
		<link>http://indietravelpodcast.com/travel-diary/travel-diary-2/</link>
		<comments>http://indietravelpodcast.com/travel-diary/travel-diary-2/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 28 May 2012 02:00:28 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Linda Martin</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Travel diary]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[a coruña]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[a coruña galicia]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Corunna]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Galicia]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[La Coruña]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[spain]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[travel blogger]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://indietravelpodcast.com/?p=7322</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>It's been a very travel-bloggery week: Dave Dean stayed with us in A Coruña until Thursday and on Sunday we travelled down to Santiago to have lunch with Sherry Ott.</p><p><a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/travel-diary/travel-diary-2/">Travel diary: work, friends, and a trip to Santiago</a> by <a rel="author" href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/author/linda/">Linda Martin</a> was originally published on <a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/">Indie Travel Podcast</a> (<a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/itunes">find in iTunes</a>). They also have <a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/books/">travel books</a> and guides to <a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/asia/">Asia</a>, <a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/europe/">Europe</a>, <a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/oceania/">Oceania</a>, <a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/south-america/">South America</a>, and more.</p>]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>It&#8217;s been a very travel-bloggery week: <a target="_blank" href="http://whatsdavedoing.com/">Dave</a> stayed with us in A Coruña until Thursday and on Sunday we travelled down to Santiago to have lunch with <a target="_blank" href="http://www.ottsworld.com/">Sherry Ott</a>.</p>
<p><strong>Monday 21/5:</strong> Our work day started late (we slept in), but having Dave around made for a lovely communal work atmosphere. After lunch Craig and I hid ourselves in our room to record the podcast, and I headed to school for a few hours while the boys kept working. </p>
<p>After dinner, I headed to Olivia&#8217;s place for a language exchange and she told me about her awesome weekend away with Guille &#8212; it sounded fantastic, full of quad biking and other adventures. </p>
<p><strong>Tuesday 22/5:</strong> Another work day, broken up nicely by a walk on the beach and a visit from Oliva in the afternoon. We&#8217;d asked her to help us with the Kindle issue: DHL was asking us for €110 in taxes on Craig&#8217;s replacement Kindle, which we didn&#8217;t want to pay. So Oliva kindly rang DHL and repeated the same story three times before finally being told that the issue was moot anyway: the Kindle was on its way back to NZ because it hadn&#8217;t been claimed. Sigh. </p>
<p>Dave, Craig and I had a relaxed evening in, which we mostly spent chatting &#8212; excellent. </p>
<p><strong>Wednesday  23/5:</strong> Since it was Dave&#8217;s last day with us, we decided to try to make the most of it. We all spent the morning working, then headed out to find a nice-looking place for lunch. We totally succeeded: our €7.50 menu del día included wine, coffee and dessert as well as the entree and main, and it was all tasty. Dave and I both had fresh delicious fish that wasn&#8217;t full of bones, and Craig chose zorza (very slightly spicy pork). </p>
<div id="attachment_7326" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 601px"><a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/wp-content/uploads/pescadilla-fish-with-its-tail-in-its-mouth.jpg"><img src="http://indietravelpodcast.com/wp-content/uploads/pescadilla-fish-with-its-tail-in-its-mouth-600x450.jpg" alt="Pescadilla" title="pescadilla - fish with its tail in its mouth" width="591" height="443" class="size-large wp-image-7326" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Pescadilla</p></div>
<p>The restaurant was halfway between our place and the Tower of Hercules, so we wandered that way so that Dave could see it up close and take a few more photos of A Coruñian views. </p>
<p>In the evening we had a tapas dinner, starting at the super-popular La Bombilla and going on to another place about five minutes&#8217; walk away &#8212; where we finally tried pimientos de Padrón (small green delicious peppers). </p>
<div id="attachment_7324" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 601px"><a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/wp-content/uploads/breogan-and-tower-of-hercules-a-corunna-spain.jpg"><img src="http://indietravelpodcast.com/wp-content/uploads/breogan-and-tower-of-hercules-a-corunna-spain-600x450.jpg" alt="Breogán and the Tower of Hercules" title="breogan and tower of hercules, a corunna, spain" width="591" height="443" class="size-large wp-image-7324" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Breogán and the Tower of Hercules</p></div>
<p><strong>Thursday 24/5:</strong> Dave&#8217;s only viable train option left at 8:50, so he had to leave the house by 7:30 to be sure of getting to the station on time. Craig accompanied him on the bus, and they managed to arrive with heaps of time to spare; they had a coffee then said a tearful goodbye (okay, I might be making that last bit up).</p>
<p><div id="attachment_7328" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 310px"><a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/wp-content/uploads/A-Coruña-beach1.jpg"><img src="http://indietravelpodcast.com/wp-content/uploads/A-Coruña-beach1-300x225.jpg" alt="A Coruña beach" title="A Coruña beach" width="300" height="225" class="size-medium wp-image-7328" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Packed!</p></div>
<p>It was a beautiful day, so after lunch we went for a longer-than-normal walk along the beach, across the isthmus and back through the city. The beach was full of sunbathers; a few brave souls headed into the water but I stayed on the dry sand, happy to be in long trousers. </p>
<p>We had quite a productive afternoon work-wise then spent the evening watching TV. </p>
<p><strong>Friday 25/5:</strong> I woke up late, with absolutely no desire to get up, so I convinced Craig to bring me breakfast in bed and spent the morning relaxing. He got a fair bit of work done, but by the time I finally got up and we had lunch, there wasn&#8217;t time for a walk. Instead, Craig came to meet me at school between classes and we had a short wander along the beach before buying pastries at the bakery near our place and eating them in the park. </p>
<p>We spent the evening doing nothing much: reading, playing computer games, chatting. </p>
<p><strong>Saturday 26/5:</strong> Ahh, a true day off. We slept in until a ridiculous hour and Craig spent the entire day playing a computer game while I did some reading, played some games, and chatted with friends in four continents. </p>
<p>Craig was too engrossed in his game to leave the house, but I headed out for the evening with Oliva and Guille and four of their friends. They introduced me to another excellent tapas restaurant as well as a cocktail bar nearby &#8212; it was a really nice evening. I got back at about 2am and called my sister, since it was her birthday (happy birthday, Anna), and we ended up chatting for an hour. It was great to catch up, although Henry did his best to distract me from the conversation by blowing me kisses every 30 seconds &#8212; very cute. </p>
<div id="attachment_7323" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 601px"><a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/wp-content/uploads/acuario-y-parque-monte-san-marco-a-coruna-spain.jpg"><img src="http://indietravelpodcast.com/wp-content/uploads/acuario-y-parque-monte-san-marco-a-coruna-spain-600x450.jpg" alt="A Coruña views" title="acuario y parque monte san marco - a coruna, spain" width="591" height="443" class="size-large wp-image-7323" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">A Coruña views</p></div>
<p><strong>Sunday 27/5:</strong> We&#8217;d organised to meet Sherry in Santiago cathedral at 1pm, and although we kind of wanted to spend the morning in Santiago, the train schedule had an unfortunate two-hour dead zone. We ended up leaving the house at 11, catching the train shortly before 12, and arriving at the cathedral at quarter to one. </p>
<p>Sherry had finished the Camino Francés the day before, but hadn&#8217;t hugged Santiago nor visited the crypt, so we made her do both before introducing her to the pilgrim institution that is Manolo&#8217;s. We had a lovely lunch and talked a lot, then visited two different cafés for drinks and more talking &#8212; it was so good to catch up!</p>
<div id="attachment_7327" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 601px"><a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/wp-content/uploads/Sherry-ott-linda-martin-craig-martin-santiago-de-compostela-spain-2012.jpg"><img src="http://indietravelpodcast.com/wp-content/uploads/Sherry-ott-linda-martin-craig-martin-santiago-de-compostela-spain-2012-600x450.jpg" alt="With Sherry in Santiago" title="Sherry ott, linda martin, craig martin - santiago de compostela, spain, 2012" width="591" height="443" class="size-large wp-image-7327" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">With Sherry in Santiago</p></div>
<p>Sherry had to head back to her accommodation to prepare for her evening flight to Barcelona, so we said our goodbyes and did our best to make it to the station for the 6:30 train back to A Coruña. No luck: we missed it by a minute. The next train wasn&#8217;t for an hour or so, so we holed up in the station bar, drinking beer and playing Ticket to Ride.</p>
<p>The trip home was pleasant and uneventful, as was our evening at home.</p>
<p><a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/travel-diary/travel-diary-2/">Travel diary: work, friends, and a trip to Santiago</a> by <a rel="author" href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/author/linda/">Linda Martin</a> was originally published on <a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/">Indie Travel Podcast</a> (<a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/itunes">find in iTunes</a>). They also have <a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/books/">travel books</a> and guides to <a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/asia/">Asia</a>, <a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/europe/">Europe</a>, <a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/oceania/">Oceania</a>, <a href="http://indietravelpodcast.com/south-america/">South America</a>, and more.</p>]]></content:encoded>
